WHEREAS, Chattanooga bested Bradley 67-65 in the quarterfinal round and defeated
Loyola-Chicago 80-73 in their semifinal match-up to advance to the title game; and
WHEREAS, the championship tilt between Chattanooga and UC Irvine was one of the
best postseason basketball games of the year, featuring fourteen lead changes and nine ties,
and neither team led by more than eight points during the contest; and
WHEREAS, Chattanooga scored with eleven seconds remaining in overtime to take a
one-point lead; the Mocs then survived a last-second attempt to claim the 2025 NIT title with a
thrilling 85-84 victory at the historic Hinkle Fieldhouse; and
WHEREAS, the Mocs were led to the promised land by NIT Most Valuable Player Trey
Bonham, who scored 19 points and pulled 10 rebounds; Collin Mulholland, who also put up 19
points; All-Tournament selection Honor Huff, who scored 14 points; Garrison Keeslar, who
made the game-winning bucket and finished with 14 points, 10 rebounds, and five assists; and
Bash Wieland, who performed yeoman's duty in posting nine points, seven rebounds, and four
assists; and
WHEREAS, the UTC squad also included contributing players, Jack Kostel, Sean
Cusano, Latif Diouf, Makai Richards, Parker Robison, Noah Melson, Ryan Lopez, Frank
Champion, Houston Holland, Liam Vitters, and Isaiah Otyaluk; and
WHEREAS, Chattanooga's NIT title would not have been possible without the expert
guidance of Head Coach Dan Earl; his assistant coaches, Ander Galfsky, Scott Greenman, and
Ricardo Rush, Jr.; and Director of Basketball Operations Alan Treakle; and
WHEREAS, the 2025 NIT title stands alongside the Mocs' league-best thirteen regular-
season SoCon titles and league-best twelve SoCon Tournament titles, UTC's 1997 run to the
Sweet Sixteen in the NCAA Tournament, and Chattanooga's 1977 NCAA Division II National
Title as one of the program's crowning achievements; and
